A '''block chain''' is a [[distributed data store]] that holds a public [[ledger]] of [[Transaction processing|transactions]] in [[cryptocurrency|cryptocurrencies]], such as [[Bitcoin]]. This record is enforced [[cryptography|cryptographically]] and hosted on machines running the software.{{R|bc1}}

Every node in a cryptocurrency having a copy of the block chain avoids the need to have a centralized database that other systems, such as PayPal, require.{{CN|date=May 2015}}

Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes, such as [[proof-of-work]], to avoid the need for a trusted third party to timestamp transactions added to the block chain. This avoids everyone [[double-spending]] the currency.{{r|kopstein}}

Developments from the first implementation, [[Bitcoin]], have built additional features for performance, anonymity, storage and [[Smart contract|smart contracts]].{{CN|date=May 2015}}

The technology forms the basis of all cryptocurrencies.{{CN|date=May 2015}}

== Implementations ==
* [[Bitcoin#Block chain|Bitcoin]] - [[Proof of work]]
* [[Namecoin]] - Ability to store [[data]] within a chain
* [[Mastercoin]] - Ability to process various transactions
* [[Peercoin]] - Additional [[Proof of stake]]

